When you encounter a new and previously unknown plant, herb, etc., what you do is quiet your mind and meditate on it, until it's almost like its spirit whispers to you what its properties are. I assume this has to do with what in Kant's time was known as "intellectual intuition".

Same friend I mentioned a while ago who studied bushcraft w/ American Indians said the way people imagine the edibility/poisonousness/"pharmacological properties" of various plants was discovered through trial and error ("a guy eating it and seeing if he dies") is very much wrong

Once this immediate knowledge of the plant's properties is obtained in meditation, you now know if it's medicinal, poisonous, edible, etc. and may use it. You need a very quiet mind to be able to do this, like a Christian ascetic monastic in a cave. No noises, mental distraction.
who else could it be

I think it's something different, because you need discernment and I think you might be confused and get it wrong if you're not well prepared so it's not a pure "revelation" in that way, maybe it's more like communicating with a forest animal and discerning from its posture etc.

Dr. Ray Peat talked about an old physiology experiment: a cat is given anesthetics to fall in a deep sleep, a recorder is attached to the cat's anal sphincter and students are told to think of a "stimulus" like tickling the cat's ear - any stimulus modifies the tone of the muscle

It's a bit weird/funny as a concept, but a very simple method to show that any touch, sensation, etc. has an effect on every part of the body, even if we are unaware of it. Ofc. in humans there will be similar effects of using certain gestures, postures, seeing other people, etc.

Of course the strong and immediate effects some stimuli can have on that specific sphincter is something many men who have met a bear when alone in the woods are well familiar with, if hunting lore is correct
For the record, because I cut the screencap too short, Kant himself believed this faculty was precluded to man
